field.value:
As of now, if the user logs out, all is well - their database entry will list them as not logged in.  But if they leave the site without specifically logging out, their cookie remains valid indefinitely.  That means an attacker could somehow get their cookie and use it for nefarious means.  Maybe.  See, the cookie contains the ip of the machine they were coming from, so if that doesn't match our database, we'll redirect them to get authenticated.  But for security's sake, maybe we should provide a mechanism to provide timeouts.

"Timeout" means that after a period of inactivity, they will be logged out.

We want them to have the ability to inactivate the timeout if they wish - like, "remain logged in" or whatever, at the login screen.  Or they could set it to log them out after 30 minutes of inactivity.  Either one should be fairly straightforward to achieve.

It will be mostly handled on the database side, but there will a client-side aspect as well.

On the database side, we can have an Event (http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/create-event.html) defined that wakes up every minute and runs some SQL that will provide the timeout capability.  

for example, something along the lines of this: 
{code}
UPDATE
FROM user u WHERE last_activity_timestamp > UTC_TIMESTAMP() + (user.timeout_time)
SET u.is_logged_in = 0;
{code}

Of course, this means we'll also need some SQL to occur every time the user reloads a page, looking something like this:
{code}
UPDATE user set last_activity_timestamp = UTC_TIMESTAMP();
{code}

On the client side, we'll want to include with the information we send a value that includes the number of seconds until the user is logged-out.  For example, we might include a div like
{code}
<div id="timeout" style="display:none">
  1234  <--------- seconds until logout occurs
</div>

and then we'll include some javascript to pop up an alert when the user gets close to that time, like 5 minutes away or something.  When the timer runs out, we reload the window to the logged-out page.
{code}

Right now, for known exceptions we have code to throw the SQLException and rollback.  However, what about cases we didn't anticipate?  If we don't have a fallback, the database can easily get locked up.  This is *only* a problem in cases where we use transactions.

So:  If a stored procedure uses START TRANSACTION...COMMIT, it *needs* the following code:


{code}

DECLARE EXIT HANDLER FOR SQLEXCEPTION
ROLLBACK;
{code}

use something like the following in a daily event:

{code}
SELECT order_id,product_name,qty FROM orders
INTO OUTFILE '/tmp/orders.txt'
{code}

and then deletes the values from the database.

comment.text:
Actually the measurements I posted previously were from my VM, which turns out is considerably slower than my main machine.  *Those* measurements actually line up with the performance I see on my *mobile* phone.

Check this, it's the create offer page with an element rendered in Bootstrap (both Bootstrap and jQuery loaded on the page): http://50.45.146.152:8080/create_requestoffer.jsp

I have it temporarily printing out 2 metrics:
     <script type="text/javascript">
       document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function(event) { 
       var newHTML = document.createElement ('div');
       newHTML.innerHTML   = '<div id="gmSomeID"><p>Document ready ms:' + (Date.now()-timerStart) + '</p></div>';
       document.body.appendChild (newHTML);

       }); 
       window.addEventListener('load', function() {
       var newHTML = document.createElement ('div');
       newHTML.innerHTML   = '<div id="gmSomeID"><p>Window load ready ms:' + (Date.now()-timerStart) + '</p></div>';
       document.body.appendChild (newHTML);
       });
     </script>

On my desktop, the difference between the original version and this is about 20ms vs 100ms.  On the phone, it's about 80ms vs 220ms.  So, on the phone, about the same difference I mentioned previously.  On my desktop, much *less* of a difference.

This isn't the total time it takes the load the page, but after downloading the jsp, it's the bulk of it (the Chrome "Inspect Element/Network" bar agrees with this as well).

The resolution to this was to add some properties to the ant script that are overridable when the script runs from the command line, like, 
{code}
ant run -Ddatabase.server=db1 -Ddatabase.username=xenosuser -Ddatabase.password=password1
{code}

also, made comments about this in the dev manual, under the heading Tomcat production configuration
